                    <h2> 1. How To Promote A Pawn</h2>
                    <p>
                    <h3>
                        Pawns have another special ability and that is that if a pawn reaches the other side of the
                        board it can become any other chess piece (called promotion) excluding a king (or pawn, for that
                        matter). A pawn is usually promoted to a queen. Only pawns may be promoted.
                    </h3>
                    </p>

                    <h2> 2. How To Do "En Passant"</h2>

                    <p>
                    <h3>
                        The last rule about pawns is called “en passant”. If a pawn moves out two squares on its first
                        move, and by doing so lands to the side of an opponent's pawn (effectively jumping past the
                        other pawn's ability to capture it), that other pawn has the option of capturing the first pawn
                        as it passes by.
                    </h3>
                    </p>


                    <h2> 3. How To Castle</h2>

                    <p>
                    <h3>
                        This move allows you to get your king to safety, and get your rook out of the corner and into
                        the game. On a player's turn he may move his king two squares over to one side and then move the
                        rook from that side's corner to right next to the king on the opposite side.
                    </h3>
                    </p>
